The approach to Yokohama, with its splendid wharves, beautiful scenery and the sun shining on grand old Fugiyama in the back ground, has been described too often to need of detailed word-pictures but, as in the case of Mr. Rosen- dale's arrival, it is often a failure because of mist shutting off the best part of the picture. Japan is as verdant as Ireland and there is a great Yariety and abundance of fruits in the empire. The sight is gratified on every hand by beautiful scenery, tnountains, hills and highly cultivated lands, all adding to the picture. Even steep hills are in a state of cultivation, the sides being terraced so as to be of use. Of the 147 ,ooo square miles in the islands, only I 2 per cent. is in a state of cultivation, and much of that has been won by the fanner only after hard work. If one should be suddenly transported from Alaska to Japan one could not tell by the people that he were in a different country. The cotn- plexions of the people of both lands are the same and many of their habits also resemble each other. The Japanese are very graceful people and their manner of salutation is especially so. They do not shake hands, and consider kissing vulgar but bow with dignity and make a hissing noise which is a sign of satisfaction. Everything in the country is srnall. Their houses are little cottages; their farms, little plots ; their railroads and cars, miniatures, their pipes and dishes on a small scale, and most of · their trees and sht·ubs dwarfs. The only really big things in the country are their mountains and their fears of Russia. Japan has always been governed by the upper class who have dragged the lower classes along through feudalism. Now education has brought them out of this state and we only find relics of it in museums. The country has a Constitu- tion, Cabinet and Parliatnent. European cloth- ing is worn by all professional men and by many of the lower classes. The only time that the educated class return to their native coshunes is in the evening when they often put on their comfortable dress to rest. It is left to the women to keep up the customs of the country in the dress which is so well known to us through photographs. It is natural for us to compare them with the Chinese, and although in America the Japanese would have the advantage of the comparison, atnong the merchants who have direct dealings with both, the opposite is the case.
